Multiplayer Game Code Architecture Design – Apex Legends
1. Game Overview
Apex Legends is a free-to-play battle royale game where squads of three players compete against other squads on a large map. Core mechanics include:
•	Hero-based characters (“Legends”) with unique abilities.
•	Squad-based combat with shooting, abilities, and teamwork.
•	Looting weapons, armor, and consumables.
•	Shrinking play zone to force encounters.
•	Matchmaking and ranking systems.
2. High-Level Architecture
Major systems required:
•	Player System Handles player profiles, stats, progression, and customization.
•	Matchmaking System Pairs players into squads and matches based on skill, rank, and latency.
•	Combat System Manages shooting mechanics, hit detection, damage calculation, and ability usage.
•	Inventory System Controls looting, equipping weapons, managing consumables, and upgrades.
•	Game State Management Tracks match phases (lobby, in-game, end-game), zone shrinking, and victory conditions.
•	UI System Displays HUD, menus, health bars, inventory, and notifications.
•	Networking System Synchronizes player actions, positions, and states across clients and servers.
3. Code Structure
Organization
•	Core Classes
o	Player: stores player data, stats, and abilities.
o	Squad: groups players together.
o	Match: manages match lifecycle and state.
o	Weapon: defines weapon properties and behaviors.
o	Ability: defines unique legend abilities.
o	Inventory: manages items and equipment.
o	GameState: tracks current phase and rules.
o	UIManager: handles HUD and menus.
o	NetworkManager: manages client-server communication.
Components
•	PlayerController: input handling, movement, ability activation.
•	CombatManager: shooting, hit detection, damage resolution.
•	MatchmakingService: squad formation, lobby management.
•	ZoneManager: shrinking play zone logic.
•	InventoryManager: loot spawning, pickup, and usage.
•	UIComponents: health bar, minimap, inventory panel.
Communication
•	Event-driven architecture: Systems communicate via events (e.g., OnPlayerDamaged, OnItemPickedUp).
•	Networking layer: Uses client-server model with authoritative server to prevent cheating.
•	Dependency injection: Ensures modularity and testability.
4. Design Decisions
•	Client-Server Model: Chosen for fairness and anti-cheat. Server is authoritative for combat and movement.
•	Component-based architecture: Allows modularity and scalability (easy to add new Legends or weapons).
•	Event-driven communication: Reduces coupling between systems and improves maintainability.
•	Separation of concerns: Each system has a clear responsibility (combat, inventory, matchmaking, etc.).
•	Scalability: Architecture supports large player counts and future expansions.

